'''Matsubara Shrine''' (松原神社, Matsubara Jinja) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Matsubara-cho (Kagoshima City)|Matsubara-cho]], [[:en:Kagoshima City|Kagoshima City]], [[:en:Kagoshima Prefecture|Kagoshima Prefecture]], Japan.
== Deities == The main deity is Yasukuni Sukunehiko no Mikoto, also known as [[Shimazu Takahisa]], the 15th head of the [[Shimazu clan]]. The shrine also enshrines the following deities in the same hall: * [[Ame-no-Minakanushi]] * [[Takamimusubi]] * [[Kamimusubi]] * [[Amaterasu]] * [[Toyouke-hime|Toyouke no Okami]] * [[Hirata Sumitada]]
; Tooth God Hirata Sumitada, a retainer of the main deity, is also enshrined. After the main deity's death, Hirata Sumitada became a nail-bound martyr. During his martyrdom, chanting and tooth-grinding sounds were heard for three days and nights, leading to his veneration as the god of teeth. He was buried next to the main deity. Even today, during the [[National Cavity Prevention Day]], the Kagoshima Dental Association holds an exodontia memorial service at the shrine.
== History == {{Seealso|Nanrinji (Kagoshima City)}} In [[Koji (Japan)|Koji]] 3 (1567), [[Shimazu Takahisa]], the reviver of the Shimazu clan, established Matsubarayama Nanrinji, a branch temple of [[Fukushoji]]. After the deity's death, [[Shimazu Yoshihisa]] designated it as the family temple, receiving significant protection from successive [[Satsuma Domain]] lords. However, in Meiji 2 (1869), during the [[Haibutsu Kishaku]] movement, the temple was abolished. The shrine was then established on the site, taking the mountain name of Nanrinji. It became a village shrine, and in [[:en:Taishō era|Taishō era]] 9 (1920), on the 350th anniversary of the deity's death, it was promoted to a prefectural shrine. Even today, it is bustling with many worshippers during festivals and the New Year holidays, located near the busy downtown area of Kagoshima.
== Sub-Shrines == * [[:en:Inari shrine|Inari shrine]] ([[:en:Inari Ōkami|Inari Ōkami]]) * [[Itsukushima Shrine]] ([[Ichikishima-hime no Mikoto]], [[Tagorihime]], [[Tagitsuhime|Tagitsuhime no Mikoto]])
