'''Matsubara Shrine''' (松原神社, Matsubara Jinja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in [[Matsubara-cho (Kagoshima City)|Matsubara-cho]], [[:en:Kagoshima City|Kagoshima City]], {{ill|Kagoshima Prefecture|en|Kagoshima Prefecture|qid=Q15701|lt=Kagoshima Prefecture|1=Kagoshima Prefecture}}, Japan.
== Deities == The main deity is Yasukuni Sukunehiko no Mikoto, also known as {{ill|Shimazu Takahisa|en|Shimazu Takahisa|qid=Q2367308|lt=Shimazu Takahisa|1=Shimazu Takahisa}}, the 15th head of the {{ill|Shimazu clan|en|Shimazu clan|qid=Q1061406|lt=Shimazu clan|1=Shimazu clan}}. The shrine also enshrines the following deities in the same hall: * [[Ame-no-Minakanushi]] * [[Takamimusubi]] * [[Kamimusubi]] * [[Amaterasu]] * {{ill|Toyouke-hime|en|Toyouke-hime|qid=Q2983724|lt=Toyouke no Okami|1=Toyouke-hime}} * [[Hirata Sumitada]]
; Tooth God Hirata Sumitada, a retainer of the main deity, is also enshrined. After the main deity's death, Hirata Sumitada became a nail-bound martyr. During his martyrdom, chanting and tooth-grinding sounds were heard for three days and nights, leading to his veneration as the god of teeth. He was buried next to the main deity. Even today, during the [[National Cavity Prevention Day]], the Kagoshima Dental Association holds an exodontia memorial service at the shrine.
== History == {{Seealso|Nanrinji (Kagoshima City)}} In [[Koji (Japan)|Koji]] 3 (1567), {{ill|Shimazu Takahisa|en|Shimazu Takahisa|qid=Q2367308|lt=Shimazu Takahisa|1=Shimazu Takahisa}}, the reviver of the Shimazu clan, established Matsubarayama Nanrinji, a branch temple of [[Fukushoji]]. After the deity's death, {{ill|Shimazu Yoshihisa|en|Shimazu Yoshihisa|qid=Q955727|lt=Shimazu Yoshihisa|1=Shimazu Yoshihisa}} designated it as the family temple, receiving significant protection from successive {{ill|Satsuma Domain|en|Satsuma Domain|qid=Q676187|lt=Satsuma Domain|1=Satsuma Domain}} lords. However, in Meiji 2 (1869), during the [[Haibutsu Kishaku]] movement, the temple was abolished. The shrine was then established on the site, taking the mountain name of Nanrinji. It became a village shrine, and in {{ill|Taishō era|en|Taishō era|qid=Q329174|lt=Taishō era|1=Taishō era}} 9 (1920), on the 350th anniversary of the deity's death, it was promoted to a prefectural shrine. Even today, it is bustling with many worshippers during festivals and the New Year holidays, located near the busy downtown area of Kagoshima.
